Now I have the full picture. The changes are:

1. When the events file doesn't exist (cold start / first run), the diagnostics now check for any stashed diagnostic error (`take_diagnostic_error()`) and display it if present — giving context about WHY state recording hasn't started yet (auth failure, config parse error, etc.).

2. When `id == "last-failure"`, instead of the generic "init state recording" advice, it now gives a structured breadcrumb trail: "No completed failed sessions exist" + a list of next evidence sources (state crashes, state doctor, state init, state tail).

3. In the fallback path when `build_why_report` fails for `last-failure`, after listing incomplete runs, it also checks for stashed diagnostic errors from the current process, surfacing them as a potential explanation.

So the theme is: on a cold start where the user asks "why last-failure" or "why <id>", instead of a bare "no events file found, run init", the diagnostics now surface any stashed startup errors AND give a structured breadcrumb trail of commands to investigate.

